		<p>&#8220;As I get older, I too rely on increasingly outdated examples.&#8221;</p>
<p>The problem with an older example is not with the example itself (which, if you are still using it years later, is almost certainly a good one).</p>
<p>The problem is that it gives the impression that, in the years since, you have not have found another good instance in which the model/technique/principle applies.  This creates the impression that the model/technique/principle has only rare applicability.</p>

