			September 12, 2016 at 11:23 pm</a>		</div>

		<p>&gt;&gt;&gt;Good methods make use of more information.&lt;&lt;&lt;</p>
<p>What&#039;s your definition of &quot;good&quot;? Isn&#039;t it quite common in, say, predictive contests for the winning algorithm to consciously discard a part of the information available?</p>
<p>Does the best algorithm always have to use all the &quot;features&quot;?</p>
<p>Why should one rate a method based on its voracious appetite for inputs?</p>

		<div class="reply"><a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='http://andrewgelman.com/2016/09/12/bayesian-statistics-then-and-now/?replytocom=307380#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm( "div-comment-307380", "307380", "respond", "29914" )' aria-label='Reply to Rahul'>Reply to this comment</a></div>
