		<li class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="comment-308226">
				<div id="div-comment-308226" class="comment-body">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
			<img alt='' src='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/e37178781b8b292ce2b85b07b9d06dfb?s=32&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/e37178781b8b292ce2b85b07b9d06dfb?s=64&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' />			<cite class="fn">Wayne Folta</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://andrewgelman.com/2016/09/12/bayesian-statistics-then-and-now/#comment-308226">
			September 13, 2016 at 12:38 pm</a>		</div>

		<p>I think the key distinction might be that &#8220;information&#8221; is not the same as data or features, implying a relevance/context and an efficiency. Sort of an information theory kind of thing.</p>
<p>In that sense, a &#8220;bad&#8221; feature may contain no information that&#8217;s relevant to the task at hand. For example, a column of random numbers. While a &#8220;good&#8221;, engineered feature can be more useful than the raw features from which it was engineered &#8212; at least in the context of the particular task and the particular prediction algorithm being used.</p>
<p>As in the old Data, Information, Insight spectrum.</p>

		<div class="reply"><a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='http://andrewgelman.com/2016/09/12/bayesian-statistics-then-and-now/?replytocom=308226#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm( "div-comment-308226", "308226", "respond", "29914" )' aria-label='Reply to Wayne Folta'>Reply to this comment</a></div>
